ions and reacting to increasingly outspoken African demands for better, and more independent, education. Through a close examination of attitudes towards race and intelligence in a British colony, Race and empire reveals how eugenics was central to colonial racial theories before World War Two.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEugenicszKenya. 0aRacismzKenya. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Africa / East.2bisacsh  a1930s.  aBritish colony.  aKenya.  acolonial racial theories.  aeugenics.  aintelligence.  apolitical preoccupations.  arace.  aracial differences.  asettler.1 aCampbell, Chloe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779135140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847791351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847791351/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles